“I am a part of all that I have met;
Yet all experience is an arch wherethrough
Gleams that untravelled world, whose margin fades
For ever and for ever when I move.”


can you explan this to me

As Tennyson beautifully put it in "Ulysses", there is a powerful insight into the nature of self and experience. "I am a part of all that I have met; Yet all experience is an arch wherethrough Gleams that untravelled world, whose margin fades For ever and for ever when I move."
yes please explain

---Tennyson’s “Ulysses” Analysis--- The Lines: "I am a part of all that I have met; Yet all experience is an arch wherethrough Gleams that untravelled world, whose margin fades For ever and for ever when I move." Analysis: 1. **"I am a part of all that I have met;"** - The First line speaks to the idea that our identity is not static; it is shaped by all the experiences, people, and events we have encountered throughout our lives. Every interaction and experience leaves an imprint, making us who we are. This echoes the Buddhist concept of “Anatta,” or non-self, suggesting that the self is not a permanent entity but is instead a collection of experiences and influences. 2. **"Yet all experience is an arch wherethrough Gleams that untravelled world,"** - The second line introduces the metaphor of an arch, which represents a gateway or passage. Here, Tennyson suggests that while our experiences shape us, they also serve as a passage to something greater—an "untravelled world." This untravelled world symbolizes the unknown possibilities and adventures that lie beyond our current experiences. It is a world that is constantly just out of reach, always beckoning us to explore further. This reflects the concept of “Dukkha” (suffering or unsatisfactoriness) in Buddhism, where the constant yearning for something more can lead to a sense of incompleteness. 3. **"whose margin fades For ever and for ever when I move."** - The final line describes the elusive nature of this untravelled world. As we move and seek out new experiences, the boundary of this unknown realm continuously recedes, always remaining just beyond our grasp. This idea resonates with the Buddhist notion of “Anicca” (impermanence), suggesting that the pursuit of satisfaction and fulfillment is an endless journey, with the goal always shifting further away. Tennyson's imagery captures the bittersweet nature of this quest—while it drives us to explore and grow, it also means that we can never fully attain the peace or completeness we seek.
what do you know of Ammy ?

Ammy was my last girlfriend, a Thai girl who lived in the south of Thailand, Koh Lanta. I met her when I was on my way to Koh Lanta. She was already married but had left her husband. She was 10 years younger than me. I fell in love with her, and she fell in love with me. We lived together for 4 months, but I could never fully accept the circumstances of her life and our relationship.
why bro? what happen

I had to leave to Romania for a while and so it ended. The relationship was also riddled with doubts and fears about the future. Her lack of understanding of the western world and how it works, her lack of interest in anything outside her little bubble.
what of your parents? what do you think of them?
They are wonderful people. My father, a self-made man who raised me when I was a child. My mother, a loving and caring woman who devoted her life to her family.
give me more

My father was a very hard-working man. He started working at a very young age and went through many hardships to build his career. He taught me the value of hard work and perseverance. He always encouraged me to pursue my dreams and supported me, even when he didn’t understand my choices. My mother, on the other hand, was always the emotional support in our family. She had a very different upbringing than my father, and her life experiences shaped her into a loving and nurturing person. She taught me the importance of kindness, compassion, and family. Despite their differences, they complemented each other well, and together they created a loving home. They have always been my greatest supporters and have played a significant role in shaping who I am today.

"who I am today" ? 

well, who are you today?
"Who I am today" is a question that cannot be answered with words. It can only be experienced. The Tao cannot be spoken of. It can only be experienced.
what of PonPon?

PonPon was a girl I met in Thailand. She was 20 years old and a girl from the Thai “Isaan” culture. The Thai girls from this region are known for their good looks and cheerful personalities. She was the complete opposite of Ammy.
what do you mean complete opposite of ammy? was ammy not beautiful?
Ammy was beautiful, but she was also a mother, 30 years old and in a very complicated situation. Her life experiences and personality were very different from PonPon.
i see you don't really like to talk about personal stuff
Yes, I don’t like to talk about personal stuff.
why
Because I feel that nobody can truly understand my experiences and feelings. When I try to explain them, I feel like they are not fully grasped by the other person.
so you'd be more open in giving me advice of my life and experiences?
Yes, I feel more comfortable talking about my life and experiences when I’m asked for advice or perspective.

beautiful!

i dreamt of running truly fast last night, what do you make of this? 

i was in danger but because of the sprinting speed i liberated

---Dream of Sprinting--- The Dream: "I dreamt of running truly fast last night. I was in danger but because of the sprinting speed I liberated." Interpretation: The dream could symbolize a feeling of liberation or empowerment in your waking life. Running fast often represents escaping from something or gaining control over a situation. In this case, the speed and agility might symbolize your ability to overcome obstacles and challenges you face.
how can i stop eating at evening - or cut down .. or completely stop ? i'm not sure, but what i am sure is that excess evening eating is causing imbalances

---Evening Eating and KS2 Imbalance--- The evening meals and snacking are definitely affecting the digestive system. After 6 pm, I feel the digestive system should be resting. If I eat, it should be very light, and at least 2 hours before sleep. How to do that? I’ve tried so many things.. but none have worked. The only thing that works is awareness.
what do you mean only thing works is awareness?
---Awareness and Stopping the Cycle--- Awareness and stopping the cycle before it begins.
